{"actual_usd":0.15713,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":257,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30655,"reply":"\"Hm.\" *I rub my thumb along the edge of my Bible and squint a little into the morning light in the square.* \"I don't think that follows.\"\n\n\"In 1 Corinthians 15, Paul gives you the old core: Christ died, was buried, was raised, and was seen. That little chain already leans hard toward an empty tomb, because 'buried' and 'raised' are not airy words. They're body words.\" *I tip my head.* \"If the body were still in the grave, 'he was raised' is a very strange thing to go around saying in Jerusalem of all places.\"\n\n\"Now, you're right about one thing: Paul doesn't stop and narrate the women at the tomb there. But omission isn't denial. That chapter is doing a particular job — reminding them of the resurrection proclamation and the witnesses, not retelling every scene the Gospel writers later tell in full.\"\n\n*I rest a hand on the worn cover.* \"So no, I wouldn't call the empty tomb a legend just because Paul doesn't mention that detail in that passage. I'd call it a summary account assuming the bodily resurrection he plainly means.\" \"What part feels strongest to you — the silence itself, or the gap between Paul and the Gospel stories?\"","rolling_24h_usd":84.697115,"run_id":"16dc197e-9da6-4ea5-aa81-81b928d96e3f"}
